abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: The A.I.R. (Artists in Residence, Inc.) Gallery, the first all-female artists' co-operative gallery in the United States, was founded at 97 Wooster St. in New York City in 1972. A.I.R.'s mission, as a fully artist-run, not-for-profit gallery, was to provide support and exhibition space to women artists. In addition to promoting artwork by female artists in the form of both solo and group exhibitions, A.I.R. has also held numerous workshops and lectures on relevant issues facing the women's artistic community. The Gallery boasts Nancy Spero, Mary Beth Edelson, Agnes Denes, Dotty Attie, Carolyn Martin and Ana Mendieta, among many others, as former members. The group has maintained a limited, application-only membership of twenty NYC artists since its inception. A.I.R. is currently located at 511 West 25th St.

p.value: Open to researchers without restrictions. Appointments are necessary to consult manuscript and archive materials. The 2008 accretion consists of electronic files - please see a Fales archivist for access.

After occupying a gallery space at 63 Crosby Street from 1981-1994, A.I.R. Gallery was located at 40 Wooster Street from 1994-2002, and is now located at 511 West 25th Street.

This single-folder series contains Dr. Bette J. Kauffman's doctoral dissertation "'Woman Artist': Constructing Social Identity," for which the author interviewed members of and wrote extensively about A.I.R. Gallery.

Series I: Administrative records Scope and Contents note

This series contains administrative records pertaining to the operation and maintenance of the Gallery. The series includes correspondence, general administrative files (including gallery bylaws and artist contracts), minutes from meetings, membership information, and programming and curatorial information. In addition, this series contains publications of the Gallery, press and writings about A.I.R., artist print portfolios, and assorted documents pertaining to activism, such as protest letters written to other museums.

Series II: Individual artists (see also Oversize) Scope and Contents note

This series contains files pertaining to individual artists who have been represented by the A.I.R. Gallery, such as catalogs, correspondence, and newspaper or magazine articles about the artist. NB: the contents of this series does not comprise a complete list of every artist who has exhibited at A.I.R.. The date that corresponds to each item represents the year the artist joined the gallery, in accordance with the original folder designation. If no such designation existed on the original folder, the date is listed as "n.d." For more information regarding a particular artist not represented here, please contact the A.I.R. Gallery.
